We can use tools to make this processs smooth for continous development, integration, deployment, testing, security, delivery and monitoring
application security.

Client-Server Architecture Mechanism, Authentication Mechanisms - OTP, RSA Tokens, username/password, private/public key based.

Server=box=node.

ssh-keygen -f var-devops - creates a public and a private key and then paste only public key in Import keypairs in AWS console to select that 
keypair while launching EC2 instance.

firewall - inbound(incoming traffic) and outbound(outgoing traffic).

We need to be in privatekey file path location and then we need to ssh to ec2 instance using "ssh -i <private-keyname> username@ipaddress" in terminal/git bash/putty etc. 
Eg: ssh -i var-devops ec2-user@13.218.246.206.

Linux Commands:
$ - normal user
# - root user
echo "text" - to print text
cd - home directory from anywhere
sudo su - switch to root user
sudo su - - go to root user home directory, i.e. /root
/home/ec2-user - default ec2 path location

uname - OS/kernel info
uname --help - info about uname command
man uname - info about uname command

pwd - present working directory
cd - change directory.
ls - l - list files and directories in alphabetical order.
ls - lr - list files and directories in reverse order.
ls - lt - list files and directories in timestamp order, i.e. latest files at top.
ls - ltr - list files and directories in reverse timestamp order, i.e. latest files at bottom.
ls -latr - list hidden(.) and visible files and directories in reverse timestamp order i.e. latest files at bottom.

touch filename.txt - creates new file.
mkdir foldername - creates new directory.
d rwx r-x r-x  - d is directory.
- rwx r-x r-x  -  - is file.
cat > filename.txt - to write content to file and enter some content and then press enter and ctrl+D to save the file.
cat >> filename.txt - to append new content to file.
cat filename.txt - read file content.
cd foldername - go to directory.
cd .. - come one step back.
rm filename.txt - remove the file.
rmdir foldername - remove the directory.
rm -r foldername - removes directory and its sub-directories.


cp filename.txt foldername/ - copy files from src to dest.
mv filename.txt foldername/ - move files from src to dest.
mv filename.txt renamedfilename.txt - rename file name.
mv filename.txt devops/renamedfilename.txt - move and rename file name in another directory.


wget <url> - download url content, used for downloading packages.
curl <url> - to view URL content, shows output on screen will not download by default, used to hit API Url's.


grep - search inside file, grep <word to search> <file>.
eg: grep -n -i user filename.txt, n gives line number, i stands for ignore case sensitive.
grep -c user filename.txt - -c gives user word occurrences.
grep -v user filename.txt - -v gives non-matching word occurrences, v stands for verbose.
grep 'architecuture$' filename.txt - $ gives words ending with architecture, and ^ gives words starting with architecture.


head filename.txt - top 10 lines
tail filename.txt - bottom 10 lines
head -n 3 filename.txt - top 3 lines
tail -n 3 filename.txt - bottom 3 lines


head -n 15 filename.txt | tail -n 10 - output of one command to input of another command using piping.
eg: cat filename.txt | grep user

cd /var/log/messages - to check linux logs
tail -f app.log - -f stands for “Follow” mode as it keeps watching the file for new lines in real time, this continuously displays appended log entries until you stop it with Ctrl+C.


cut - to process and extract text.
eg: echo "Varun/Appalla"
cut -d "/" -f1 , i.e. cut words using "/" delimiter, -f1 here is first fragment .i.e. Varun.

eg: cat /etc/passwd - shows linux users with ":" as fragments.
cut -d ":" -f1,3 /etc/passwd - prints first and third fragments.


awk - to process and extract text, more advanced than cut.
eg: echo "Varun/Appalla"
awk -F "/" '{print $NF}' - prints last fragment , i.e. Appalla.

eg: cat /etc/passwd - shows linux users with ":" as fragments.
awk -F ":" '{print $1F,$3F}' /etc/passwd - prints first and third fragments.
awk -F ":" '$3>1000 {print $1F,$3F}' users - prints users with id more than 1000.

history - all previous commands.
Ctrl+r - to enable reverse search and give any command , for eg: search using wget and we get all its previous entered commands starting from wget.
will be displayed where were used earlier.
clear - clear the screen.
exit - exit from current session.


Vim Editor - open using vim filename.txt
esc mode, command/colon mode(:) and insert mode(i).

esc mode:
gg - goes to top of file.
Shift+g - goes to bottom of file.
u - undo last change.
Ctrl+r - redo last change.
dd - deletes line.
yy - copy the line.
p - paste below the line.
Shift+p - paste above the line.


command/colon mode(:):
.wq - to save the file and quit.
.q - quit.
.q! - quit without saving changes.
:set nu - display number lines.
:<lineno> - to go to that respective line.
:/<wordtosearch> - to search for that word - searches from top to bottom.
:?<wordtosearch> - to search for that word - searches from bottom to top.
:<linenumber>d - deletes 2nd line.
:%d - deletes all lines.
:noh - stop highlighting words.
:<line-number>s/<wordtofind>/<replacedword> - replaces first occurrence in that line.
:<line-number>s/<wordtofind>/<replacedword>/g - replaces all occurrences in that line.
:%s/<wordtofind>/<replacedword>/g - replaces all occurrences in all the lines.

insert mode:
i - insert mode.


User Management:
user, group, others
u , g , o

useradd ramesh  - creates ramesh user.
id ramesh - view ramesh user, group info.

User in linux will have one primary group and atleast one secondary group.

groupadd devops - create devops group.
cat /etc/group - display all groups.

usermod -g devops ramesh - adds ramesh user to devops group, now his default groups will be removed and he will be added to devops group
usermod -aG testing ramesh  - adds ramesh user to secondary group, i.e. testing group along with devops group as primary group.

passwd ramesh - create the password for ramesh user.

ssh ramesh@<ipaddress> , it gives permission denied as linux by default only accepts key-based auth, hence we need to emnable password based auth.
For that, we need to go to vim /etc/ssh/sshd_config and search for PasswordAuthentication and change option from no to yes and save and close 
the file, i.e :wq.

sshd -t - to check if sshd file is correct without errors.
systemctl restartd sshd - restart sshd service.

ssh ramesh@<ipaddress> - now ramesh can login with his password to that EC2 instance.

How to give sudo access to ramesh:
We can use "usermod -aG wheel ramesh" - to add ramesh to wheel group, and now ramesh will have sudo access for all commands.

For giving ramesh to access only specific "systemctl" command instead of complete sudo access such as logging as sudo user, adding/removing users etc,
we need to go to vim /etc/sudoers file and add this line under wheel command:
ramesh ALL=(ALL) /usr/bin/systemctl

visudo -c - to check if sudoers file is correct without errors.

gpasswd -d ramesh wheel - remove ramesh from wheel group.

usermod -L ramesh - locks user ramesh to prevent him to login to server.

gpasswd -d ramesh testing - remove ramesh from testing group.

usermod -g ramesh ramesh - adds ramesh user to ramesh group, this will add him back to initial ramesh primary group.

Before removing ramesh, we need to take backup of this files, hence we login as sudo access and give 
taf -cf /root/ramesh.tar.gz /home/ramesh to create ramesh.tar.gz zip file in root folder and we can extract it using tar -xf ramesh.tar.gz and
ls -l to see ramesh directory.

tar -cf devops.tar.gz devops - creates devops folder tar zip file.
tar -xf devops.tar.gz -  extracts devops zip file content.

userdel -r ramesh - removes ramesh user and his home directory.

Permissions:
Only the Owner of file or root user can change access levels.
u g o - user group others
eg:
chmod o+x users.txt
chmod o-x users.txt
chmod ugo+x users.txt

or we can use 4 2 1 nos for r w x permissions.

eg:
chmod 764 users.txt

Ownership:
Only root user can change file ownership.
chown <user>:<group>
eg: sudo chown ec2-user:devops linux - will change only owner directory.
sudo chown -R ec2-user:devops linux - will change owner directory and owner subdirectories also.

Employee Joins organization - he wil generate public key and send it to admins, for admins to give access to EC2 servers to him.
now add him ->
sudo useradd ram
sudo su - 
cd /home/ram and ls -la
mkdir .ssh and ls -la 
cd .ssh/ and touch authorized_keys and vim authorized_keys and paste his public key here.
cd .. and ls -la
chowm ram:ram -R .ssh and cd .ssh and ls -la.
chmod 600 authorized_keys
cd .. and ls -la
chmod 700 .ssh
groupadd devops
usermod -g devops ram
cd /etc/sudoers.d/ and ls -l 
vim devops and enter %devops ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD:ALL

Now ram can login using ssh to ec2 instance with ssh - i ram ram@<ipaddress> and add other users etc such as sudo useradd Mahesh as he got 
root access enabled, i.e. ALL=(ALL) in /etc/sudoers.d/ file.


