nginx - web server to host FE static web pages, can also be used as reverse proxy.
/etc/nginx - nginx configs
/usr/share/nginx/html - configure html pages
/usr/share/nginx/html/index.html - default nginx html page
/var/log/nginx/error.log - nginx error logs
/etc/nginx/conf.d/*.conf - nginx conf file


A forward proxy sits in front of clients to manage outbound traffic, masking user identities and bypassing restrictions.
Configured and known to the client.
Used for Content filtering, bypassing censorship, privacy


A reverse proxy sits in front of servers to manage inbound traffic, distributing requests to backend applications 
while protecting the origin servers from direct exposure.
Completely hidden from the client.
Used for Load balancing, SSL termination, DDoS protection.

HTTPS Methods - get, post, put, patch, delete.

ICANN (Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and Numbers) is a global, nonprofit public-benefit corporation headquartered in the United States. 
It is responsible for coordinating the maintenance and procedures of critical databases related to the namespaces and numerical spaces of the Internet,
ensuring the network's stable, secure, and interoperable operation.

Domain Name System (DNS) Management: Coordinates the root server system and oversees generic Top-Level Domains (gTLDs like .com, .org) 
and country-code TLDs (ccTLDs like .uk, .jp).

IP Address Allocation: Manages and distributes Internet Protocol (IP) version 4 and version 6 addresses to regional registries.


TLD root servers, formally known as DNS root name servers, are the master directory of the Internet. 

They sit at the top of the Domain Name System (DNS) hierarchy and translate human-readable domain names (like .com or .org) into machine-readable IP addresses 
by directing queries to the appropriate Top-Level Domain (TLD) servers.

There are 13 original logical root name servers identified by letters A through M.

Domain registers such as godaddy checks wih TLD if domain is avaialble, if available it collects the details such as company, name, address
etc, and after payment, godaddy updates TLD about buyer and domain details and then we need to create one A record against domain register.

Browser-Cache-OS-Cache-ISP DNS Resolver-Cache-Root Servers-TLD information-Contact TLD-Go Daddy-Fetch A record for us.

Give AWS hosted zone name servers in hostiger name servers to route hostinger domain to AWS Route 53 service.

Types of Records:
NS(Name servers)- who is managing the domain and responsible to provide IP address.
A record - Holds IP address of domain.
SOA(DNS Start of Authority) record is a mandatory resource record that stores essential administrative information about a domain zone.
A - Holds IPv4 IP address.
AAAA - Holds IPv6 IP address.
MX - Mail records.
TXT - Text Records
CName - Canonical Name.
eg: nslookup -type=CNAME google.vardevops.online and it gives us www.google.com as CNAME, as in EC2 instances, CNAME default type is A, hence
we need to explicitly mention type as CNAME.


TTL - time to live - how many secs for changes to get reflected.

nslookup vardevops.online - to check if domain is reflected with our given IP address.
nslookup mongodb.vardevops.online - to check if mongodb.vardevops.online domain is reflected with mongodb private IP address.

No of ways to check if server is up and running:
curl -v http://localhost:8080/health,  eg: {"app":"OK","mongo":true}, -v for more data
telnet IPaddress Portno,  eg: telnet mongodb.vardevops.online 27017
ps -ef | grep node,  eg: roboshop   14619       1  1 07:51 ?        00:00:00 /bin/node /app/server.js
systemctl status service-name , eg: Active: active (running) since Thu 2026-06-11 07:51:12 UTC; 3min 15s ago
netstat -lntp,  eg: tcp6       0      0 :::8080                 :::*                    LISTEN      14619/node  

HTTP status codes:
100X,200X,300X,400X,500X


To check logs:
