Linux file-structure hierarchy:
/bin - essential user binaries/commands/softwares
/boot - files/process/commands required for OS booting
/dev - includes mouse,keyboard , usb device interface, EBS volumes etc
/etc - extra configuration files related to system packages, user installed packages
/home - user related files etc, /home/username
/lib and /lib64 - all required libraries
/media - removable disks like dvd, usb are mounted here
/mnt - mount extra disks in linux server for temp purpose
/opt - can be stored here when software is installed manually, eg; /opt/roboshop
/proc - processer info, eg: cat /proc/cpuinfo, /proc/meminfo,/proc/uptime, cd /proc and ls -l - running process info related to kernel is displayed
/root - root user home directory
/run - running process info
/sbin - root user essential binaries/commands/softwares
/srv - service , data related to system like html directory etc, eg; /srv/www, /srv/ftp
/swap - virtual RAM, if swap usage is more, it indicates system is under stress
/sys - kernel subsystems info
/tmp - temporary files and directories to be stored here
/usr - specific user related utilities/applications
/var - variable and log files , eg: /var/lib/docker


How to add extra disk to linux server:
1.create EBS(Elastic Block Storage) volume
2.attach to instance and create partition.
3.Create file system, xfs is best for AWS
4.Create data folder, -p create if folder is not there or ignore it
5.Mount nvme1n1p1 partition to the created data folder

network disk - google drive, one driver, S3 etc, hard disk - physical device, latency is less.
DB are always stored in hard disk, normal files such as images and objects are stored in network disk.
hard disk can be attached only to one machine, network disk can be attched to multiple servers.

EBS is like harddisk, hence should be in same availability zone as EC2 server, eg: 1f.


Go to AWS-Volumes and Create new volume of 20GB and attach to required instance and give lsblk in terminal to check attached disk storage,
nvme0n1 is the root disk  - 20G, used for OS default purposes.
eg: our created new disk is nvme1n1 - 20G  - used for DB related data, other imp files and configurations are stored here.

sudo parted /dev/nvme1n1 --script mklabel gpt mkpart primary 0% 100%
Now nvme1n1 will have this below - nvme1n1p1, i.e. divided into 1 part.


sudo mkfs.xfs -f /dev/nvme1n1p1 and df -hT 

sudo mkdir -p data 

sudo mount /dev/nvme1n1p1 /data

give df -hT and now observe that /dev/nvme1n1p1 is mounted on /data

sudo blkid /dev/nvme1n1p1 - to generate UUID to store this disk partition permanently and note this UUID for adding to /etc/fstab file

sudo vim /etc/fstab and add this -> UUID="UUID" /data xfs defaults,nofail 0 2

sudo mount - a -> test mount configuration

To modify and extend nvme1n1 disk storage from 20G to 35G , we do in AWS console->volumes and to extend its disk partition's memory, we use below commands:
sudo growpart /dev/nvme1n1 1
xfs_growfs /data 
df -hT /data - to check extended disk partition memory.

Memory Management:
df -hT - check disk info such as storage etc
free -m - check ram storage
free -h - check ram storage in MB's
top - running commands info such as memory, cpu utilisation etc
ps aux --sort -rss | head -10 - top 10 memory usage running process
cd /var and give du -sh * - check which files are consuming more memory inside that specific folder


inode = Stores metdata of file/directory such as filr type, owner, permissions, size, memory block address etc.
stat <filename.txt> - to see file metadata.
inode does not store its actual file content.


symlink/Shortlink/Softlink ->  Like a shortcut file/directory.
eg: ln -s links.txt ../linux.txt link - creates softlink for linux.txt using link, stands with l. eg: lrwx wx rwx

stat link and stat linux.txt - has different inode nos for symlinks.

inode no is different for symlinks files and original files.
Symlink can be created for files and directories and symlink can be created across all different filesystems.
If actual file is removed, symlink will be broken.
Used for version switching and roll backing.
ln -sfn dnf-4 dnf - switch force link, for upgrading/rollback purposes.

YUM package manager - before RHEL 8.
DNF Package manager - From RHEL 8.


hardlink -  cannot be created in another filesystem.
hardlink file is same as original file, but maybe different name.
inode no is same for hardlinks files and original files.
They point to same memory location, so memory is not wasted.
hardlink cannot be created for directories.
hardlinks are used for backup.
When all hard links are deleted, then only original file will be deleted.
sudo find /home -xdev -inum 524430 - gives all files related to that inum within that file system.

eg: ln aws.txt aws-1.txt.